t women make up 25% of their workforce.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nA graphic designer in Brooklyn told the<a href=\"https://nypost.com/2018/12/08/construction-company-rolls-out-first-inclusive-at-work-signs/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">New York Post</a>, I applaud whoever designed them. I didn\'t realize there are women interested in doing that sort of work.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.plazaconstruction.com/profile/leadership/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">Plaza CEO Richard Wood</a>told the NYP that the company began switching out the old \'Men at Work\' signs in September as part of their female-friendly initiative, saying that it encourages women to enter the industry by creating a gender-neutral workplace environment.\r\n\r\nRead more about Plaza Construction and how they are leading the way in making it easier for women to participate in a male-dominated field:\r\n\r\n<b>Plaza Construction Takes Steps To Close The Gender Gap</b>\r\n\r\nBy Autumn Cafiero Giusti\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.constructor-digital.com/ngcs/0119_january_february_2019/MobilePagedArticle.action?articleId=1452704\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.constructor-digital.com/ngcs/0119_january_february_2019/MobilePagedArticle.action?articleId=1452704</a>\r\n\r\n<i>THE \"MEN AT WORK\" sign is as much a part of the jobsite as hard hats and bulldozers, and its one of the images most commonly associated with the construction industry. But although its probably unintentional, these signs overlook a fact thats becoming harder for the industry to ignore  women work on construction sites, too.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Construction company rolls out first inclusive at work signs</b>\r\n\r\nBy Dean Balsamini | New York Post | December 8, 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://nypost.com/2018/12/08/construction-company-rolls-out-first-inclusive-at-work-signs/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://nypost.com/2018/12/08/construction-company-rolls-out-first-inclusive-at-work-signs/</a>\r\n\r\nHardhat Ayesha Butt, 22, an apprentice electrician at 100 Varick St., where a 25-story condo is being built, said the new slogan helps combat the stigma faced by female construction workers. It makes people know there are females doing the job and getting into the field, she said.\r\n\r\n<b>S&amp;P Global Showcases the Benefits of Greater Women\'s Participation in the Workforce</b>\r\n\r\nPR Newswire | January 24, 2019\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://finance.yahoo.com/news/p-globals-changepays-showcases-benefits-145500628.html\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://finance.yahoo.com/news/p-globals-changepays-showcases-benefits-145500628.html</a>\r\n\r\nIncreasing women\'s participation in the workforce could add USD $5.87 trillion to the value of global markets: S&amp;P Global\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/bmJgm4AxmeA\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','Men and Women At Work','','publish','closed','closed','','men-and-women-at-work','','','2019-02-01 17:26:07','2019-02-01 17:26:07','',0,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/?p=599',0,'post','',0),(600,1,'2019-02-01 17:25:41','2019-02-01 17:25:41','','blog_6','','inherit','closed','closed','','blog_6','','','2019-02-01 17:25:41','2019-02-01 17:25:41','',599,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/blog_6.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(601,1,'2019-02-01 17:25:53','2019-02-01 17:25:53','A construction company in New York City has begun using new gender-inclusive Men and Women at Work signsand it may just be the first of its kind in the city.\r\n\r\nIn 2017, women accounted for 7% of the construction workforce in NYC and 9% nationally. A spokesperson for<a href=\"https://www.plazaconstruction.com/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">Plaza Construction</a>said that women make up 25% of their workforce.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nA graphic designer in Brooklyn told the<a href=\"https://nypost.com/2018/12/08/construction-company-rolls-out-first-inclusive-at-work-signs/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">New York Post</a>, I applaud whoever designed them. I didn\'t realize there are women interested in doing that sort of work.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.plazaconstruction.com/profile/leadership/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">Plaza CEO Richard Wood</a>told the NYP that the company began switching out the old \'Men at Work\' signs in September as part of their female-friendly initiative, saying that it encourages women to enter the industry by creating a gender-neutral workplace environment.\r\n\r\nRead more about Plaza Construction and how they are leading the way in making it easier for women to participate in a male-dominated field:\r\n\r\n<b>Plaza Construction Takes Steps To Close The Gender Gap</b>\r\n\r\nBy Autumn Cafiero Giusti\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.constructor-digital.com/ngcs/0119_january_february_2019/MobilePagedArticle.action?articleId=1452704\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.constructor-digital.com/ngcs/0119_january_february_2019/MobilePagedArticle.action?articleId=1452704</a>\r\n\r\n<i>THE \"MEN AT WORK\" sign is as much a part of the jobsite as hard hats and bulldozers, and its one of the images most commonly associated with the construction industry. But although its probably unintentional, these signs overlook a fact thats becoming harder for the industry to ignore  women work on construction sites, too.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Construction company rolls out first inclusive at work signs</b>\r\n\r\nBy Dean Balsamini | New York Post | December 8, 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://nypost.com/2018/12/08/construction-company-rolls-out-first-inclusive-at-work-signs/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://nypost.com/2018/12/08/construction-company-rolls-out-first-inclusive-at-work-signs/</a>\r\n\r\nHardhat Ayesha Butt, 22, an apprentice electrician at 100 Varick St., where a 25-story condo is being built, said the new slogan helps combat the stigma faced by female construction workers. It makes people know there are females doing the job and getting into the field, she said.\r\n\r\n<b>S&amp;P Global Showcases the Benefits of Greater Women\'s Participation in the Workforce</b>\r\n\r\nPR Newswire | January 24, 2019\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://finance.yahoo.com/news/p-globals-changepays-showcases-benefits-145500628.html\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://finance.yahoo.com/news/p-globals-changepays-showcases-benefits-145500628.html</a>\r\n\r\nIncreasing women\'s participation in the workforce could add USD $5.87 trillion to the value of global markets: S&amp;P Global\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/bmJgm4AxmeA\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','Men and Women At Work','','inherit','closed','closed','','599-revision-v1','','','2019-02-01 17:25:53','2019-02-01 17:25:53','',599,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/?p=601',0,'revision','',0),(602,1,'2019-01-23 17:27:07','2019-01-23 17:27:07','The construction industry is the second highest among all industries in the abuse of alcohol and illicit drug. Just about one in six construction workers uses illicit drugs and 20% report current heavy alcohol use.\r\n\r\nFor a contractor, the costs in lost time and production can be devastating. Just in the Midwest alone, the costs rose to<a href=\"https://midwestepi.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/opioids-and-construction-final2.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">$5.2 billion in 2015</a>. And<a href=\"https://geniebelt.com/blog/what-is-osha\">OSHA</a>has put tougher rules in place for contractors who struggle to maintain a drug-free work environment.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nTesting after work-related injuries and illnesses must have an \'objectively reasonable basis, they saynot one thats discriminatory or retaliatory in nature. Policies that call for automatic testing after an injury are not allowed by the new rules. This is so workers won\'t be discouraged from reporting incidents.\r\n\r\nCreating a drug-free workplace and complying with testing requirements may not be a priority for some construction contractors, but it can become an unbearable cost to ignore.\r\n\r\nPhil Casto from Construction Executive details some simple steps, identified by HUB International, that contractors can take to encourage and ensure a drug-free workplace.\r\n\r\nStep 1: Update Your Policies.\r\n\r\nStep 2: Update DFWP Testing Protocols.\r\n\r\nStep 3: Provide Training.\r\n\r\nStep 4: Provide an Employee Assistance Program.\r\n\r\nStep 5: Investigate Health and Wellness Programs.\r\n\r\n<b>Five Steps for the Construction Industry to Take to Build a Drug-free Workplace</b>\r\n\r\nBy Phil Casto | Construction Executive | October 30, 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://constructionexec.com/partner-article/5-steps-for-the-construction-industry-to-take-to-build-a-drug-free-workplace\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">http://constructionexec.com/partner-article/5-steps-for-the-construction-industry-to-take-to-build-a-drug-free-workplace</a>\r\n\r\n<i>Construction firms that work aggressively to counter the dangers of on-the-job use of drugs and alcohol can only benefit over the long term with healthier employees, fewer issues like absenteeism, accidents, turnover and theft, and heightened morale and productivity.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Countering Substance Abuse in Construction</b>\r\n\r\nHUB International\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.hubinternational.com/-/media/Form-Assets/Countering_Substance_Abuse_In_Construction.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.hubinternational.com/-/media/Form-Assets/Countering_Substance_Abuse_In_Construction.pdf</a>\r\n\r\nIncreasing substance abuse and safety incidents creates an opportunity to promote health and wellness in construction. Learn how you can create a drug-free workplace to protect your workers and maintain your rating as an employer of choice.\r\n\r\n<b>The Silent Killer On The Job Site: Inside Construction\'s Battle With Opioids</b>\r\n\r\nCameron Sperance, Chuck Sudo | Forbes | October 26, 2017\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/bisnow/2017/10/26/the-silent-killer-on-the-job-site-inside-constructions-battle-with-opioids/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.forbes.com/sites/bisnow/2017/10/26/the-silent-killer-on-the-job-site-inside-constructions-battle-with-opioids/</a>\r\n\r\nThe trillion-dollar industry has been hit harder than almost any other sector of the economy in a health crisis that takes nearly 100 American lives each day. But it has been largely silent, more concerned about perception than the number of workers who are addicted to opioids.\r\n\r\n<b>Substance Abuse By Industry</b>\r\n\r\nDonna M. Bush, Ph.D., Rachel N. Lipari, Ph.D. | SAMHSA | April 16, 2015\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/report_1959/ShortReport-1959.html\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/report_1959/ShortReport-1959.html</a>\r\n\r\nThe highest rates of past month heavy alcohol use among full-time workers aged 18 to 64 were found in the mining (17.5 percent) and construction industries (16.5 percent).\r\n\r\n<b>The Impact of a Skilled Labor Shortage in Construction</b>\r\n\r\nby Tyler Riddell | eSub | February 8, 2017\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://esub.com/impact-skilled-labor-shortage-construction/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://esub.com/impact-skilled-labor-shortage-construction/</a>\r\n\r\nThe impact of the skilled labor shortage in construction has continued to plague the construction industry since the recession (2007-2011) where approximately 2 million construction workers were let go (more than any other industry). Ever since then, the construction industry has not been able to make up for this loss of skilled labor and has struggled to fulfill the many construction jobs that are becoming more readily available.\r\n\r\n<b>Addressing the Opioid Epidemic Among Midwest Construction Workers</b>\r\n\r\nFrank Manzo IV, Jill Manzo | Midwest Economic Policy Institute | February 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://midwestepi.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/opioids-and-construction-final2.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://midwestepi.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/opioids-and-construction-final2.pdf</a>\r\n\r\nConstruction is one of the most physically demanding and dangerous occupations in the United States. The injury rate for construction workers is 77 percent higher than the national average for other occupations. In addition, an estimated 15 percent of construction workers have a substance abuse disorder, compared to the national average of 8.6 percent.\r\n\r\n<b>The Evolving Drug Crisis in Construction</b>\r\n\r\nPhil Casto, Mingee Kim, Kathryn Russo | Hub International\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://webinars.constructionexec.com/webinar/the-evolving-drug-crisis-in-construction/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://webinars.constructionexec.com/webinar/the-evolving-drug-crisis-in-construction/</a>\r\n\r\nWEBINAR. March 6, 2 p.m. EST. Given the physical wear and tear associated with construction work, builders are susceptible to opioid abuse. Almost one in six construction workers uses illicit drugs, and industry opioid spend is 5 percent to 10 percent above every other industry.','The Drug-Free Workplace','','publish','closed','closed','','the-drug-free-workplace','','','2019-02-01 17:30:01','2019-02-01 17:30:01','',0,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/?p=602',0,'post','',0),(603,1,'2019-02-01 17:29:31','2019-02-01 17:29:31','','blog_7','','inherit','closed','closed','','blog_7','','','2019-02-01 17:29:31','2019-02-01 17:29