ruction-industry-to-take-to-build-a-drug-free-workplace\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">http://constructionexec.com/partner-article/5-steps-for-the-construction-industry-to-take-to-build-a-drug-free-workplace</a>\r\n\r\n<i>Construction firms that work aggressively to counter the dangers of on-the-job use of drugs and alcohol can only benefit over the long term with healthier employees, fewer issues like absenteeism, accidents, turnover and theft, and heightened morale and productivity.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Countering Substance Abuse in Construction</b>\r\n\r\nHUB International\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.hubinternational.com/-/media/Form-Assets/Countering_Substance_Abuse_In_Construction.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.hubinternational.com/-/media/Form-Assets/Countering_Substance_Abuse_In_Construction.pdf</a>\r\n\r\nIncreasing substance abuse and safety incidents creates an opportunity to promote health and wellness in construction. Learn how you can create a drug-free workplace to protect your workers and maintain your rating as an employer of choice.\r\n\r\n<b>The Silent Killer On The Job Site: Inside Construction\'s Battle With Opioids</b>\r\n\r\nCameron Sperance, Chuck Sudo | Forbes | October 26, 2017\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/bisnow/2017/10/26/the-silent-killer-on-the-job-site-inside-constructions-battle-with-opioids/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.forbes.com/sites/bisnow/2017/10/26/the-silent-killer-on-the-job-site-inside-constructions-battle-with-opioids/</a>\r\n\r\nThe trillion-dollar industry has been hit harder than almost any other sector of the economy in a health crisis that takes nearly 100 American lives each day. But it has been largely silent, more concerned about perception than the number of workers who are addicted to opioids.\r\n\r\n<b>Substance Abuse By Industry</b>\r\n\r\nDonna M. Bush, Ph.D., Rachel N. Lipari, Ph.D. | SAMHSA | April 16, 2015\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/report_1959/ShortReport-1959.html\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/report_1959/ShortReport-1959.html</a>\r\n\r\nThe highest rates of past month heavy alcohol use among full-time workers aged 18 to 64 were found in the mining (17.5 percent) and construction industries (16.5 percent).\r\n\r\n<b>The Impact of a Skilled Labor Shortage in Construction</b>\r\n\r\nby Tyler Riddell | eSub | February 8, 2017\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://esub.com/impact-skilled-labor-shortage-construction/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://esub.com/impact-skilled-labor-shortage-construction/</a>\r\n\r\nThe impact of the skilled labor shortage in construction has continued to plague the construction industry since the recession (2007-2011) where approximately 2 million construction workers were let go (more than any other industry). Ever since then, the construction industry has not been able to make up for this loss of skilled labor and has struggled to fulfill the many construction jobs that are becoming more readily available.\r\n\r\n<b>Addressing the Opioid Epidemic Among Midwest Construction Workers</b>\r\n\r\nFrank Manzo IV, Jill Manzo | Midwest Economic Policy Institute | February 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://midwestepi.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/opioids-and-construction-final2.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://midwestepi.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/opioids-and-construction-final2.pdf</a>\r\n\r\nConstruction is one of the most physically demanding and dangerous occupations in the United States. The injury rate for construction workers is 77 percent higher than the national average for other occupations. In addition, an estimated 15 percent of construction workers have a substance abuse disorder, compared to the national average of 8.6 percent.\r\n\r\n<b>The Evolving Drug Crisis in Construction</b>\r\n\r\nPhil Casto, Mingee Kim, Kathryn Russo | Hub International\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://webinars.constructionexec.com/webinar/the-evolving-drug-crisis-in-construction/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://webinars.constructionexec.com/webinar/the-evolving-drug-crisis-in-construction/</a>\r\n\r\nWEBINAR. March 6, 2 p.m. EST. Given the physical wear and tear associated with construction work, builders are susceptible to opioid abuse. Almost one in six construction workers uses illicit drugs, and industry opioid spend is 5 percent to 10 percent above every other industry.','The Drug-Free Workplace','','inherit','closed','closed','','602-revision-v1','','','2019-02-01 17:30:01','2019-02-01 17:30:01','',602,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/?p=604',0,'revision','',0),(605,1,'2019-01-22 17:31:09','2019-01-22 17:31:09','Misconceptions about the nature of construction work, combined with the notion that a four-year college degree is a universal necessity, may be keeping a lot of talented people from entering the field.\r\n\r\nFirst of all, construction requires a lot of education. Jonathan Arnholz of<a href=\"http://discover.byf.org/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">NCCER</a>reminds us that construction requires a high level of specialized skill, which is only obtained through training and experience. He says that construction pros need to be able to pair creativity and a keen eye with precision and meticulous detail.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nCraft professionals aren\'t merely doing hard, mindless labor  theyre performing detailed, specialized work that requires a high level of talent. The construction industry seems to have been marginalized due to some distorted and long-standing stereotypes.\r\n\r\nAccording to Jonathan, here are the top 5 misconceptions about construction:\r\n\r\n1. Construction is Unskilled Labor\r\n\r\n2. Working in Construction Means Youre Uneducated\r\n\r\n3. Construction is Just Building Houses\r\n\r\n4. Construction is Only for Men\r\n\r\n5. Construction is Unsafe\r\n\r\nRead what Jonathan has to say at the<a href=\"http://www.byf.org/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">Build Your Future</a>website:\r\n\r\n<b>Top 5 Misconceptions About Construction</b>\r\n\r\nJonathan Arnholz | BYF | January 15, 2019\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.byf.org/blog/news-item/top-5-misconceptions-about-construction/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">http://www.byf.org/blog/news-item/top-5-misconceptions-about-construction/</a>\r\n\r\n<i>Despite the major role construction plays in society, the industry has been marginalized. Long-standing stereotypes contribute to a poor public attitude toward construction, while the push for four-year degrees has placed craft careers in a perceived lower tier of work. Were here to bust a few myths.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>The Misguided Priorities of Our Educational System</b>\r\n\r\nBy Oren Cass | New York Times | Dec. 10, 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/10/opinion/college-vocational-education-students.html\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/10/opinion/college-vocational-education-students.html</a>\r\n\r\nA second explanation is the widespread belief that a college diploma is a necessary and sufficient ticket to the middle class. If that were true, even a small chance at escaping the supposedly sad fate of inadequate education is better than ever admitting defeat.','Misconceptions About Construction','','publish','closed','closed','','misconceptions-about-construction','','','2019-02-01 17:33:10','2019-02-01 17:33:10','',0,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/?p=605',0,'post','',0),(606,1,'2019-02-01 17:32:38','2019-02-01 17:32:38','','blog_8','','inherit','closed','closed','','blog_8','','','2019-02-01 17:32:38','2019-02-01 17:32:38','',605,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/blog_8.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(607,1,'2019-02-01 17:33:10','2019-02-01 17:33:10','Misconceptions about the nature of construction work, combined with the notion that a four-year college degree is a universal necessity, may be keeping a lot of talented people from entering the field.\r\n\r\nFirst of all, construction requires a lot of education. Jonathan Arnholz of<a href=\"http://discover.byf.org/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">NCCER</a>reminds us that construction requires a high level of specialized skill, which is only obtained through training and experience. He says that construction pros need to be able to pair creativity and a keen eye with precision and meticulous detail.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nCraft professionals aren\'t merely doing hard, mindless labor  theyre performing detailed, specialized work that requires a high level of talent. The construction industry seems to have been marginalized due to some distorted and long-standing stereotypes.\r\n\r\nAccording to Jonathan, here are the top 5 misconceptions about construction:\r\n\r\n1. Construction is Unskilled Labor\r\n\r\n2. Working in Construction Means Youre Uneducated\r\n\r\n3. Construction is Just Building Houses\r\n\r\n4. Construction is Only for Men\r\n\r\n5. Construction is Unsafe\r\n\r\nRead what Jonathan has to say at the<a href=\"http://www.byf.org/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">Build Your Future</a>website:\r\n\r\n<b>Top 5 Misconceptions About Construction</b>\r\n\r\nJonathan Arnholz | BYF | January 15, 2019\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.byf.org/blog/news-item/top-5-misconceptions-about-construction/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">http://www.byf.org/blog/news-item/top-5-misconceptions-about-construction/</a>\r\n\r\n<i>Despite the major role construction plays in society, the industry has been marginalized. Long-standing stereotypes contribute to a poor public attitude toward construction, while the push for four-year degrees has placed craft careers in a perceived lower tier of work. Were here to bust a few myths.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>The Misguided Priorities of Our Educational System</b>\r\n\r\nBy Oren Cass | New York Times | Dec. 10, 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/10/opinion/college-vocational-education-students.html\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/10/opinion/college-vocational-education-students.html</a>\r\n\r\nA second explanation is the widespread belief that a college diploma is a necessary and sufficient ticket to the middle class. If that were true, even a small chance at escaping the supposedly sad fate of inadequate education is better than ever admitting defeat.','Misconceptions About Construction','','inherit','closed','closed','','605-revision-v1','','','2019-02-01 17:33:10','2019-02-01 17:33:10','',605,'http://absdsgn.com/dev/moffitt/?p=607',0,'revision','',0),(608,1,'2019-01-20 17:35:13','2019-01-20 17:35:13','The<a href=\"https://www.nccer.org/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">National Center for Construction Education and Research</a>(NCCER) conducted a<a href=\"https://www.agc.org/sites/default/files/Files/Communications/2018_Workforce_Survey_National.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">survey</a>for 2018 that shows salaries for construction industry craft positions in the U.S. are still rising. The survey includes a list of the average annual salaries for<a href=\"https://www.nccer.org/docs/default-source/pdfs/2018_constructioncraftsalarysurvey.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">32 categories of workers</a>.\r\n\r\nThe NCCER promotes careers in construction. Its a nonprofit created by the construction industry for designing and developing standardized curriculum with portable credentials and to help respond to the shortage in a skilled construction workforce.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nAlthough a few salary categories decreased in 2018 (tower crane operator, welder, and heavy equipment operator), others (HVAC technicians, sheet metal, scaffold builders) saw salaries increase by 12% to 30%.\r\n\r\nRead about the national survey and its encouraging results from NCCER:\r\n\r\n<b>Salaries Are On The Rise In The Construction Industry</b>\r\n\r\nPress Release | NCCER | December 12, 2018\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nccer.org/docs/default-source/press-release/craft-salary-survey-final.pdf\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.nccer.org/docs/default-source/press-release/craft-salary-survey-final.pdf</a>\r\n\r\n<i>Of the 32 construction positions surveyed, average annual salaries ranged from $47,700 to $92,500. Project supervisors and program managers topped the list, earning over $88,000 and $92,500 respectively. Professions earning more than $65,000 include boilermaker, mobile crane operator, tower crane operator, millwright, industrial electrician, power line worker, pipe welder, instrumentation technician and combo welder. Additionally, seven more craft areas made more than $60,000 per year.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Salaries for many construction trades on the rise</b>\r\n\r\nBy Kim Slowey | Construction Dive | January 2, 2019\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.constructiondive.com/news/survey-salaries-for-many-construction-trades-on-the-rise/544739/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">https://www.constructiondive.com/news/survey-salaries-for-many-construction-trades-on-the-rise/544739/</a>\r\n\r\nA survey conducted by the National Center for Construction Education and Research (NCCER) has revealed that<a href=\"https://www.nccer.org/news-information/press-releases/detail/salaries-are-on-the-rise-in-the-construction-industry\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">salaries for many skilled craft positions</a>in the construction industry continued to rise in 2018.\r\n\r\n<b>Build Your Future Initiative</b>\r\n\r\nNational Center for Construction Education &amp; Research\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.byf.org/resources/\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">http://www.byf.org/resources/</a>\r\n\r\nBuild Your Future aims to be the catalyst 